 wrinkle free. Research also shows that the levels of zinc and niacin in ground turkey may also help treat inflammatory acne.\r\n\r\nYour next cookout will also help your complexion if you serve this surprising take on a hamburger.\r\n\r\n<strong>Turkey Burgers With Mango and Avocado Salsa</strong> Servings: 4\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients: </strong>\r\n\r\n1 pound turkey, ground\r\n\r\n1/2 tsp salt\r\n\r\n1/2 tsp pepper, black, ground\r\n\r\n1/2 tsp garlic powder\r\n\r\n1/2 medium onion, chopped\r\n\r\n1 large egg\r\n\r\n1/2 cup bread crumbs, whole wheat\r\n\r\n1 medium mango, peeled, seeded, and diced\r\n\r\n1 medium pepper, red bell, diced\r\n\r\n1 medium avocado, peeled, seeded, and diced\r\n\r\n1 Tbsp sugar, white, granulated\r\n\r\n2 Tbsp vinegar, white wine\r\n\r\n1 Tbsp oil, olive\r\n\r\n1/2 tsp salt\r\n\r\n2 whole hamburger buns, whole wheat\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n\r\n1. Place turkey in a large mixing bowl. Add in salt, pepper, garlic powder, onion, egg, and bread crumbs and mix thoroughly being careful not to over mix.\r\n\r\n2. Form turkey mixture into 4 patties.\r\n\r\n3. Cook patties over medium heat in a lightly-oiled frying pan or on a lightly-oiled grill.\r\n\r\n4. Cook for 5-10 minutes per side, until cooked through and internal temperature reaches 165 degrees F.\r\n\r\n5. As the burgers cook, prepare the salsa by combining the mango, pepper, avocado, sugar, vinegar, oil, and salt in a medium bowl. Toss to combine.\r\n\r\n6. Place burgers open-faced on top of half of a bun. Top with salsa and serve.\r\n','Help Fight Inflammatory Acne','','inherit','open','open','','1776-revision-v1','','','2015-06-30 18:03:54','2015-06-30 18:03:54','',1776,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1776-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1931,1,'2015-06-30 17:44:14','2015-06-30 17:44:14','Does Shaving Make the Hair Thicker and Darker?\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-1817 alignright\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/shaving-leg-300x198.jpg\" alt=\"shaving-leg\" width=\"300\" height=\"198\" />\r\n\r\nHave you ever noticed that after a clean shave, once your hair begins to grow back, it feels different? The truth is that shaving does not cause the hair to grow back thicker or darker. It simply puts all of the hairs in the same growth cycle, causing them to grow at the same rate, which gives the illusion of a thicker beard. Shaving also blunts the ends of the hair, which can appear lighter due to sun exposure. With the less pigmented ends gone, your hair may appear darker when it grows back in. Stubble causing you trouble?\r\n\r\nSchedule a free consultation to learn more about laser hair removal and be free of shaving!','Be Free of Shaving','','inherit','open','open','','1816-revision-v1','','','2015-06-30 17:44:14','2015-06-30 17:44:14','',1816,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1816-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1930,1,'2015-06-30 17:44:06','2015-06-30 17:44:06','<b>Some things just come better in pairs.</b>\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-1820 alignright\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/peanut-butter-and-jelly-600x420-300x210.jpg\" alt=\"peanut-butter-and-jelly-600x420\" width=\"300\" height=\"210\" />\r\n\r\nLike, peanut butter and jelly. Bread and butter, cheese and wine, spaghetti and meatballs, coffee and donuts. <i>Mmm</i>.\r\n\r\nAnd venturing out of food pairings: twins (Mary-Kate and Ashley!).  Shoes. Diamond earrings...etc...\r\n\r\n<b>Retina and Sunscreen</b> anyone? The perfect duo, the ultimate power couple – the Sonny and Cher – of skincare products. Retina is an anti-aging product which exfoliates and helps reduce fine lines, wrinkles, pore size and brown spots. Sunscreen protects the skin from photo damage, premature aging, unwanted sun damage and lose of collagen.\r\n\r\nIt’s all about balance, you see.\r\n\r\nOther dynamic duos? Let us know in the comments below.','Better Together','','inherit','open','open','','1819-revision-v1','','','2015-06-30 17:44:06','2015-06-30 17:44:06','',1819,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1819-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1925,1,'2015-06-30 17:43:07','2015-06-30 17:43:07','Exciting things are happening at Lebo! Due to expanding our York office, we are looking for friendly, goal-oriented, customer service focused individuals who would like to join our team!\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-1889 aligncenter\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/lebo-staff-photo-2014-300x95.png\" alt=\"lebo-staff-photo-2014\" width=\"300\" height=\"95\" />\r\n\r\nLebo is a one of a kind skin care center and we pride ourselves on the experience and individualized attention we offer our patients.\r\n\r\nListed below are the available positions:\r\n\r\n1. Full time Receptionist (York Office)\r\n\r\n2. Part-time Provider Assistant (York Office)\r\n\r\n3. Full time Provider Assistant (York Office)\r\n\r\n4. Part-time Receptionist (Hanover Office)\r\n\r\nPlease email Dalia Rutledge at <a href=\"mailto:drutledge@leboskincare.com\">drutledge@leboskincare.com</a> or call 717-747-9950 ext. 111.','Job Posting','','inherit','open','open','','1888-revision-v1','','','2015-06-30 17:43:07','2015-06-30 17:43:07','',1888,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1888-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1934,1,'2015-06-30 17:46:05','2015-06-30 17:46:05','<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-1783 alignright\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/sweet-potatos-240x300.jpg\" alt=\"sweet potatos\" width=\"240\" height=\"300\" />\r\n<h2>Sweet Potatoes</h2>\r\nA healthy alternative to plain potatoes, sweet potatoes contain high levels of beta-carotene (what gives these tubers their trademark orange pigment). In addition to its antioxidant benefits, beta-carotene helps to encourage skin cell turnover, so the skin\'s surface looks smooth and fresh.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re not sure how to handle a sweet potato, follow this easy recipe for the super spud.\r\n\r\n<strong>Baked Sweet Potatoes</strong> Servings: 2\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n\r\n2 medium potatoes, sweet\r\n\r\n2 tsp butter\r\n\r\n1/4 tsp salt\r\n\r\n1/2 tsp cinnamon, ground\r\n\r\n1 tsp sugar, white, granulated\r\n\r\n2 Tbsp yogurt, Greek, non-fat or low-fat, vanilla (optional)\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions: </strong>\r\n\r\n1. Preheat oven to 450 degrees F. Wash sweet potatoes, scrubbing them thoroughly.\r\n\r\n2. Place potatoes on a baking sheet and bake in pre-heated oven for 35 to 45 minutes, or until a knife can be easily inserted into the center.\r\n\r\n3. Cut each potato down the middle. Top with butter, salt, cinnamon, and sugar.\r\n\r\n4. Serve with a dollop of yogurt, if desired.','Smooth Skin with Sweet Potatoes','','inherit','open','open','','1782-revision-v1','','','2015-06-30 17:46:05','2015-06-30 17:46:05','',1782,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1782-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1926,1,'2015-06-30 17:43:26','2015-06-30 17:43:26','<h2><a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/sweet-potatos.jpg\"><img class=\" size-medium wp-image-1783 alignright\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/sweet-potatos-240x300.jpg\" alt=\"sweet potatos\" width=\"240\" height=\"300\" /></a></h2>\r\n<h2>Sweet Potatoes</h2>\r\nA healthy alternative to plain potatoes, sweet potatoes contain high levels of beta-carotene (what gives these tubers their trademark orange pigment). In addition to its antioxidant benefits, beta-carotene helps to encourage skin cell turnover, so the skin\'s surface looks smooth and fresh.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re not sure how to handle a sweet potato, follow this easy recipe for the super spud.\r\n\r\n<strong>Baked Sweet Potatoes</strong> Servings: 2\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n\r\n2 medium potatoes, sweet\r\n\r\n2 tsp butter\r\n\r\n1/4 tsp salt\r\n\r\n1/2 tsp cinnamon, ground\r\n\r\n1 tsp sugar, white, granulated\r\n\r\n2 Tbsp yogurt, Greek, non-fat or low-fat, vanilla (optional)\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions: </strong>\r\n\r\n1. Preheat oven to 450 degrees F. Wash sweet potatoes, scrubbing them thoroughly.\r\n\r\n2. Place potatoes on a baking sheet and bake in pre-heated oven for 35 to 45 minutes, or until a knife can be easily inserted into the center.\r\n\r\n3. Cut each potato down the middle. Top with butter, salt, cinnamon, and sugar.\r\n\r\n4. Serve with a dollop of yogurt, if desired.','Smooth Skin with Sweet Potatoes','','inherit','open','open','','1782-revision-v1','','','2015-06-30 17:43:26','2015-06-30 17:43:26','',1782,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1782-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1927,1,'2015-06-30 17:43:38','2015-06-30 17:43:38','<h2><a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/shrimp.jpg\"><img class=\" size-medium wp-image-1780 alignright\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/shrimp-240x300.jpg\" alt=\"shrimp\" width=\"240\" height=\"300\" /></a></h2>\r\n<h2>Shrimp</h2>\r\nThese tiny shellfish have big nutrition benefits. They contain a potent antioxidant (it\'s what gives them their pink color), and they contain omega-3s for additional antioxidant power. Plus, these little guys also contain zinc, an excellent anti-inflammatory that scientists have found can help reduce acne breakouts.\r\n\r\nToss together this refreshing salad for a tasty way to keep your skin healthy.\r\n\r\n<strong>Garden Salad with Shrimp</strong> Servings: 1\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients: </strong>\r\n\r\n2 cups lettuce, red leaf\r\n\r\n1/2 medium carrot, peeled and sliced\r\n\r\n1/2 medium cucumber, sliced\r\n\r\n1/2 medium pepper, red bell, sliced\r\n\r\n1/4 small avocado, sliced\r\n\r\n2 Tbsp lemon vinaigrette\r\n\r\n3 oz. shrimp, medium, pre-cooked\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n\r\n1. Rinse and thoroughly dry lettuce. Place in a large serving bowl.\r\n\r\n2. Add carrot, cucumber, pepper, and avocado slices.\r\n\r\n3. Add lemon vinaigrette. Toss to coat ingredients evenly.\r\n\r\n4. Top with shrimp and serve.','Antioxidant Power','','inherit','open','open','','1779-revision-v1','','','2015-06-30 17:43:38','2015-06-30 17:43:38','',1779,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1779-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1928,1,'2015-06-30 17:43:46','2015-06-30 17:43:46','<a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/how-do-i-get-rid-of-whiteheads-on-my-face3.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-1849 alignright\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/how-do-i-get-rid-of-whiteheads-on-my-face3-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"how-do-i-get-rid-of-whiteheads-on-my-face3\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a>\r\n\r\nWe\'ve all seen them and have all wanted to get rid of them. Those tiny white bumps on your skin we call whiteheads.  You have to get real close to even see them and they are simply blocked pores which have not developed further into zits. Dermatologists still can’t explain why some blocked pores just sit there while others quickly turn into monster zits which spoil your day. Some people don’t get whiteheads at all, while others do. Dead cells of the whitehead are not hardened like blackheads, and are practically invisible. Make sure you are washing your face regularly and using the Warming Exfoliating Green Tea Scrub 2-3 times a week will also help prevent you from getting them.','What are Whiteheads?','','inherit','open','open','','1848-revision-v1','','','2015-06-30 17:43:46','2015-06-30 17:43:46','',1848,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1848-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1929,1,'2015-06-30 17:43:57','2015-06-30 17:43:57','<a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/inflammatory-acne.jpg\"><img class=\" size-medium wp-image-1777 alignright\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/inflammatory-acne-240x300.jpg\" alt=\"inflammatory acne\" width=\"240\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n<h2>Ground Turkey</h2>\r\nLean protein, such as ground turkey provides skin with the building blocks for collagen and elastin, the fibers that help skin look firm and wrinkle free. Research also shows that the levels of zinc and niacin in ground turkey may also help treat inflammatory acne.\r\n\r\nYour next cookout will also help your complexion if you serve this surprising take on a hamburger.\r\n\r\n<strong>Turkey Burgers With Mango and Avocado Salsa</strong> Servings: 4\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients: </strong>\r\n\r\n1 pound turkey, ground\r\n\r\n1/2 tsp salt\r\n\r\n1/2 tsp pepper, black, ground\r\n\r\n1/2 tsp garlic powder\r\n\r\n1/2 medium onion, chopped\r\n\r\n1 large egg\r\n\r\n1/2 cup bread crumbs, whole wheat\r\n\r\n1 medium mango, peeled, seeded, and diced\r\n\r\n1 medium pepper, red bell, diced\r\n\r\n1 medium avocado, peeled, seeded, and diced\r\n\r\n1 Tbsp sugar, white, granulated\r\n\r\n2 Tbsp vinegar, white wine\r\n\r\n1 Tbsp oil, olive\r\n\r\n1/2 tsp salt\r\n\r\n2 whole hamburger buns, whole wheat\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n\r\n1. Place turkey in a large mixing bowl. Add in salt, pepper, garlic powder, onion, egg, and bread crumbs and mix thoroughly being careful not to over mix.\r\n\r\n2. Form turkey mixture into 4 patties.\r\n\r\n3. Cook patties over medium heat in a lightly-oiled frying pan or on a lightly-oiled grill.\r\n\r\n4. Cook for 5-10 minutes per side, until cooked through and internal temperature reaches 165 degrees F.\r\n\r\n5. As the burgers cook, prepare the salsa by combining the mango, pepper, avocado, sugar, vinegar, oil, and salt in a medium bowl. Toss to combine.\r\n\r\n6. Place burgers open-faced on top of half of a bun. Top with salsa and serve.\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Help Fight Inflammatory Acne','','inherit','open','open','','1776-revision-v1','','','2015-06-30 17:43:57','2015-06-30 17:43:57','',1776,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1776-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1933,1,'2015-06-30 17:44:46','2015-06-30 17:44:46','When temperatures drop and the weather takes a turn for the worst, it’s easy to forget about your skin when all you’re trying to do is stay warm. During the winter months it’s crucial to take the extra steps to protect your skin from the harsh elements. The biggest skin concerns during this time of the year tend to be dehydration and sun damage. Here are six tips on how to keep your skin beautiful during the winter months.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/winter-girl.jpg\"><img class=\" size-medium wp-image-1767 alignright\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/winter-girl-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"winter girl\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>1. Drink Water</b>\r\n\r\nTo keep your skin glowing and beautiful make sure you drink water consistently throughout the day. This is an important step not only for your skin, but for the entire well-being of your body. Water can detoxify your skin while helping regulate your body temperature and even help you lose weight!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>2. Take Warm Showers, Not Hot </b>\r\nIt’s tempting to turn your shower up to full heat when it’s freezing outside, but that’s actually worse for your skin. Hot water strips your skin of its natural oils and dries it out. Instead, opt for a warm shower that will be more gentle and nourishing to the skin.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>3. Exfoliate</b>\r\nExfoliation is equally important during wintertime because as our skin dries out it can becomes flaky and tight. <a href=\"http://www.walgreens.com/store/c/st.-ives-fresh-skin-invigorating-apricot-scrub/ID=prod5564510-product\">The</a> Warming Green Tea Exfoliating Scrub works wonders on the skin and can instantly get rid of any dryness or flakiness in one wash. Follow this up with a moisturizer and your skin will be glowing in no time.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>4. Moisturize</b>\r\nAfter exfoliating the skin; applying your moisturizer right after exfoliating helps your skin absorb the moisture so that it will last all day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>5. Sunscreen</b>\r\nMake sure to apply a layer of SPF before applying any makeup. Unlike summertime, in the winter it’s easy to forget about sun damage because you aren’t outside as much and the sun may be covered by clouds. But your risk of getting a good sunburn can be just as high on an overcast day than it is on a sunny one. So make sure to apply an SPF of at least 30 for protection.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>6. Lip Balm</b>\r\nOn the lips, always make sure to swipe a quick layer of lip balm on to nourish and protect them throughout the day. Stop in and pick up a lip balm ($1.49) the best part is that it has an SPF of 15 to help prevent UV damage.\r\n\r\nNow that you have all the skin secrets for winter go ahead and try them out! They will be sure to keep your skin healthy and glowing during the cold months ahead.','6 Tips to Keep Your Skin Healthy This Winter','','inherit','open','open','','1766-revision-v1','','','2015-06-30 17:44:46','2015-06-30 17:44:46','',1766,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1766-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1936,1,'2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','5 SKIN CARE QUESTIONS: T. Nicole Kelley\n\nNicole is a graduate of York College with a Bachelor of Science Degree in Nursing along with a Masters of Science in Nursing from the University of Maryland.As well as being a member of the Lebo team, she currently holds a position with The Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery Team at Shock Trauma Center as an Acute Care Nurse Practitioner. With over 20 years of practice and teaching, Nicole has developed a fantastic reputation with her patients and colleagues.\n\n<b>1.       </b><b>How would you describe your skin type?</b>\n\nAging, Acne occasionally. Tolerant to most skin care treatments.  Fitzpatrick III, Tan easily with sunblock, but with resultant freckles.\n\n<b>2.       </b><b>What is the best skin care advice anyone ever gave you?</b>\n\nLimit exposure to direct sun. Sunblock SPF&gt;30\n\n<b>3.       </b><b>In your opinion, what is the single most important thing you can do for your skin?</b>\n\nIf you could only choose one product for skin care, if should be a Retina/Retinol at night and minimize sun exposure.\n\nBut the reality is you should do as much as you can to protect your skin. (skin care with patient-specific appropriate products, peels, laser therapies, microdermabrasion etc) If you had hypertension, you would do all of the following:\n\nLose weight, exercise, eat a healthy diet, control diabetes, and take appropriate medications…Not just take medications without the other treatments (same goes for your skin)\n\n<b>4.       </b><b>What is your personal skin care routine like?</b>\n\nI have a twice a day skin care routine including a cleanser with glycolic acid to exfoliate, moisturizer, sunblock during the day and retina at night…sprinkled with active products such as hydroquinone for lightening, vitmin C, HGF, salicylic acid during breakouts\n\n<b>5.       </b><b>What is your first skin care memory?</b>\n\nIn my 20’S I knew I didn’t want to get wrinkles…so I invested in a skin care regimen called “Nuveau”. However I was not very compliant.\n\nI received my first Botox in my late 30’s because I was tired of my co-workers asking me if I was mad…Which I was almost NEVER mad while at work.\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><strong>We can’t thank Nicole enough for the great interview! </strong></em></p>','Employee Spotlight: Nicole','','inherit','open','open','','1769-revision-v1','','','2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','',1769,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1769-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1937,1,'2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','<a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/lebo-feb-2015-newsletter-1.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1789\" alt=\"lebo-feb-2015-newsletter-1\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/lebo-feb-2015-newsletter-1.png\" width=\"600\" /></a>\n<a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/lebo-feb-2015-newsletter-2.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1790\" alt=\"lebo-feb-2015-newsletter-2\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/lebo-feb-2015-newsletter-2.png\" width=\"600\" /></a>\n','February 2015 Lebo Skin Care Newsletter','','inherit','open','open','','1791-revision-v1','','','2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','',1791,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1791-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1938,1,'2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','NEW YEAR’S SKIN CARE RESOLUTIONS\nSo January is almost over and I think now is a good time to discuss New Year’s Resolutions. So many people think just because the calendar says January 1st, it’s the beginning of starting something new. Because of this concept, we will provide a realistic list of things you can stick to…feel free to add what you have put on your own list:\n<a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/new_year_2015_background_hq1.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1739\" alt=\"new_year_2015_background_hq\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/new_year_2015_background_hq1.jpg\" width=\"448\" height=\"229\" /></a>\nNew Year’s Skin Care Resolutions!!!\n\n1. Stay Hydrated: Water is very important. Your body depends on water for survival. Did you know that water makes up more than half of your body weight? Every cell, tissue and organ in your body needs water to function correctly.\n2. Exercise: Have you ever heard the expression \"use it or lose it\"? It\'s true! If you don\'t use your body, you will surely lose it. Your muscles will become flabby and weak. Your heart and lungs won\'t function efficiently. And your joints will be stiff and easily injured. Inactivity is as much of a health risk as smoking!\n3. Diet: Eating in this manner helps you maintain your body’s everyday functions, promotes optimal body weight and can assist in disease prevention.\n4. Sleep: Next to eating sleeping is one of the most important things for your body. Sleep is good for your body and good for your skin. I’m sure you’ve seen what happens to how you look when you don’t get enough. During the sleep cycle is when your body goes into repair mode, skin included.\n5. Wash your face before bed: We all need down time, and so does our skin. Our skin needs time to breathe and repair itself. If it is coated in makeup 24/7 then it does not get the time it needs to restore itself. You also miss out on the ability for nighttime power products to do their jobs. Night time is great for applying your AHA (alpha hydroxy acid) based products that encourage cell turnover leading to younger skin.\n6. Cleaning out your closet: Embrace who you are now and love yourself now. Resolve to stay healthy and that doesn’t always mean skinny. Give your skinny/bigger clothes to charity, share with your co-workers or sell them on ebay. Get a great pair of jeans that suit your body type and size and rock them!\n7. Cleaning out your medicine cabinet and make-up bag: Throw away those old, dirty make up sponges at the bottom of your make up bag. Wash your make up brushes and toss that old make-up out and start fresh. Old make-up and brushes hold bacteria that can spread and cause acne breakouts.\n8. Make it out to the salon: Nothing like some waxing or a manicure and pedicure to make you feel pretty and polished. Feeling good about yourself carries over to all other parts of your life. Work on it in the New Year. Good self-esteem is important and a salon trip is a fun and inexpensive treat to help you boost yourself up once in a while. We can all use it from time to time.\n9. Don’t pick at your skin: Picking slows the healing process and may lead to spreading and hyperpigmentation on the skin.\n10. Try! Make an effort to get on a real skin care regimen customized for your specific skin concerns. If you all of a sudden find yourself stressing every time you look in the mirror, maybe it’s time you make a little effort to help yourself out. All the tools you need are right here.\n11. Sunscreen daily: We can’t stress this enough. It should be right up there with wearing your seat belt. Wearing sunscreen is the #1 anti-aging tip of the skin care world. Sun exposure causes the most preventable damage on your skin. Period.\n\nBest wishes to you in 2015. Happy and Healthy!!! It’s never too late to start making positive changes in your life. Certainly don’t wait for what the calendar says.','New Year\'s Skin Care Resolutions','','inherit','open','open','','1738-revision-v1','','','2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','',1738,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1738-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (1939,1,'2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','An apple a day keeps the doctor away goes the old adage. But did you know that apples can also keep acne at bay? Apples contain pectin, a type of dietary fiber that absorbs toxins and pushes them through the colon fast. In addition to pectin, apples are a good source of bioflavonoids and vitamins which help maintain skin health. \n\nApple and Onion Soup\n6 servings\n<a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/apple-and-onion-soup.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/apple-and-onion-soup.jpg\" alt=\"apple and onion soup\" width=\"290\" height=\"217\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1742\" /></a>\n\n	Ingredients\n	1 Tbsp canola oil\n2 medium yellow onions, sliced\n1 small leek, chopped\n1/2 Tbsp fresh rosemary, chopped\n1/2 Tbsp fresh thyme\n3 organic apples, cut into small dices\n6 cups fat-free, low-sodium vegetable broth\n\nDirections\n•	Heat the oil in a medium saucepan over medium heat. Add the onions and sauté until golden.\n•	Pour in the broth and bring to the boil over medium-high heat. Add the apples, and reduce the heat to medium-low. Simmer for 10 minutes.\n\n\n','Apple and Onion Soup','','inherit','open','open','','1741-revision-v1','','','2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','',1741,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1741-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1940,1,'2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','DO CERTAIN FOODS REALLY IMPROVE YOUR SKIN?\n<a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/do-certain-foods-really-affect-your-skin.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1745\" alt=\"do certain foods really affect your skin\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/do-certain-foods-really-affect-your-skin.jpg\" width=\"425\" height=\"282\" /></a>\n\nWho doesn’t love to eat? Of course the real question is: Who doesn’t love to eat foods that are very bad for us? The answer is no one. It is common knowledge that a healthy diet and lifestyle has been shown to prolong your life and the quality of your life. What about the positive effects these things have on the skin?\n\nWhen we take the last bite of that king size candy bar (really?), we think to ourselves: are we going to still fit into our jeans by the weekend? We’re not usually thinking about the long and short term effects it will have on our complexions. We know that eating junk food doesn’t cause pimples. That’s an old school myth. We do know now however that eating junk food and not enough of the good stuff does actually have an impact on the aging and appearance of the skin.\n\nThe internet had some interesting facts about the correlation between certain foods and skin health. I found a lot of cool stuff. The Center for Disease Control or the CDC, has something called The National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey. There are tons of these surveys being done for different demographics and foods. Once study conducted showed that intake of high Vitamin C foods (citrus fruits, red peppers, tomatoes) is associated with a lower risk of wrinkled and dryness in middle-aged women. This may be due to the antioxidant properties of Vitamin C and its role in keeping the skin firm due to its effect on collagen synthesis.\n\nBlackberries, plums, strawberries and blueberries have the highest antioxidant content of any foods according to the Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry. Now consider eating these things when not dropped into a pitcher of sangria or dipped in fondue.\n\nAnother recent study from the American Journal of Clinical Nutrition showed that of 1100 Australian adults (and we know that big ol’ hole in the ozone is right over them) over 5 years, precancerous lesions on the skin were decreased by 30 percent in those who ate 5oz or more of omega-3 rich fish each week. Actinic Keratoses are skin lesions that show up from chronic sun exposure and may develop into cancer if left untreated. Scientists believe that the omega-3’s act as a shield against free radical damage in the cell walls and offer anti-inflammatory protection to the skin. Now they are not saying that eating fish and omega-3 rich foods replace using sunscreen. Just interesting to know that good nutrition does effect the skin in a positive way.\n\nThe last thing we want to mention. Sugar. The low carb craze is pretty much over because really, who can live without having a bagel. A side of bacon just doesn’t sound so appealing anymore unless accompanied by some pancakes. Sugar and high-glycemic carbohydrates which are junky carbs like anything with white flour and the processed garbage we seem to live on like crackers, cereal, rice, potatoes, and breads, can cause glycation. A fancy word for a process in which sugar attaches to proteins in the bloodstream forming harmful molecules called Advanced Glycation End Products that breakdown the collagen and elastin in the skin, speeding up the aging process. Cutting out bad carbs and processed food from your diet even for just a few days makes a huge difference in how you look and feel. You should try it.\n\nBasically of all the information available about good skin foods it all boils down to this: Antioxidants (berries, tomatoes, broccoli) and omega-3 fatty acids (salmon, albacore tuna) and eating way less processed foods are the things that are going to make the difference. Overall good nutrition for overall good health, skin included. No one said you can’t eat a little junk in moderation.','Do Certain Foods Really Improve Your Skin?','','inherit','open','open','','1744-revision-v1','','','2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','',1744,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1744-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1941,1,'2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','<img class=\" wp-image-1596 alignleft\" alt=\"5 skin care tips\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/5-skin-care-tips.jpg\" width=\"269\" height=\"179\" />This is where you type <strong>stuff</strong>. asdfas asdf add fas fads f asdf as dfas df asdf as fas dfa sdf','Keeping Your Hair Safe Over The Summer','','inherit','open','open','','1624-revision-v1','','','2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','',1624,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1624-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1942,1,'2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','<a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/lebo-jan-2015-newsletter-1.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1727\" alt=\"lebo-jan-2015-newsletter-1\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/lebo-jan-2015-newsletter-1.png\" width=\"600\" /></a>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/lebo-jan-2015-newsletter-2.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1728\" alt=\"lebo-jan-2015-newsletter-2\" src=\"http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/lebo-jan-2015-newsletter-2.png\" width=\"600\" /></a>','January 2015 Lebo Skin Care Newsletter','','inherit','open','open','','1725-revision-v1','','','2015-07-01 13:50:17','2015-07-01 13:50:17','',1725,'http://www.gavinadvertising.com/leboskincare.com/1725-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(1944,1,'2015-07-01 14:15:21','2015-07-01 14:15:21','Easter Seals is the leading non-profit provider of services for individuals with autism, developmental disabilities and other specific needs. This year, Lebo had 4 teams compete in Office Olympix. In total, Lebo Skin Care Center raised $5359.75. Click the images below to view full size.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1945,1946,1947,1948,1949\"]','Easter Seals Office Olympix 2010','Easter Seals is the leading non-profit provider of services for individua